  "chunk_index": 11,
  "summary": "While tying his shoelace, Hastings encounters Megan Barnard, the sister of the deceased Elizabeth \"Betty\" Barnard. Megan, a fashionable woman with a short black bob, arrives by taxi carrying a small suitcase and initially treats Hastings with suspicion and defiance. She asserts that Betty was a \"good girl\" with no male friends, a comment Hastings perceives as a mockery of the media's tendency to idealize the dead.\n\nMegan leads Hastings to a kitchen where he is joined by Hercule Poirot. Upon recognizing Poirot as a private detective, Megan admits that while she liked her sister, she considered her a \"fool.\" She provides a photograph of a blonde girl with a mischievous smile, describing herself as the \"plain\" sister in comparison.\n\nMegan reveals that Betty enjoyed attention from handsome men and would banter with customers at the Saffron Cat Cafe, despite her intention to marry Donald Fraser. While Megan initially describes Donald as a calm and steady man, Poirot probes deeper, suggesting he may possess violent or jealous tendencies. Megan eventually becomes more truthful, admitting that Donald is naturally jealous and struggles to understand why Betty seeks the company of other men despite her affection for him.",
